const String legalDocumentRahmenvertrag_en = r'''
FRAMEWORK AGREEMENT
for wholesalers
(As of [insert date])

between

ABU, Adel Group
Dubai, United Arab Emirates
(hereinafter “platform operator”)

and

the respective registered wholesaler
(hereinafter “wholesaler”)

1. Conclusion of the framework agreement

1.1 By submitting the electronic registration application on the platform, the wholesaler makes a binding offer to conclude this framework agreement.

1.2 The requirements for registration are in particular:

– Complete entry of company data
– Upload a valid trade license or commercial register extract
– Providing tax identification data
– Agreement to the General Terms and Conditions
– Consent to data protection regulations
– Agree to compliance guidelines
– Submission of a self-declaration of compliance with all legal requirements

1.3 The framework agreement comes into effect as soon as the platform operator checks the registration application and expressly activates the account. Activation takes place by activating the user account or by corresponding electronic confirmation.

1.4 There is no right to activation. The platform operator is entitled to reject registrations without giving reasons.

2. Subject of the contract

2.1 The subject of this contract is the use of the digital B2B platform to market and distribute goods to registered retailers.

2.2 The platform operator exclusively provides the technical infrastructure. He does not become a contractual partner in the purchase contracts concluded via the platform.

2.3 Purchase contracts are concluded exclusively between wholesalers and retailers.

3. Use of the Platform

3.1 After activation, the wholesaler is entitled to connect his goods to his merchandise management system via a technical interface.

3.2 The wholesaler is entitled to discontinue regular offers as well as special offers, minimum purchase quantities, bundle offers and time-limited promotions.

3.3 The wholesaler undertakes to process all transactions initiated or concluded via the platform exclusively via the platform.

3.4 It is prohibited to continue or conclude contract negotiations or orders that were initiated via the platform outside of the platform, in particular to avoid platform fees.

4. Obligations of the wholesaler

4.1 The wholesaler undertakes to make all offers posted legally permissible, complete and truthful.

4.2 If offers from retailers are accepted, the wholesaler undertakes to properly execute the contract.

4.3 The wholesaler undertakes not to jeopardize the reputation and integrity of the platform.

4.4 The wholesaler maintains confidentiality regarding all non-public data, prices, special conditions and business models on the platform.

4.5 The wholesaler expressly undertakes not to enter into price agreements that violate antitrust law or other agreements that restrict competition.

5. Rights to content and intellectual property rights

5.1 The wholesaler warrants that it has all necessary rights to brands, product images, texts and other content.

5.2 The wholesaler grants the platform operator a simple, non-transferable right of use to display the posted content within the platform, process it technically and make it accessible to registered users.

5.3 The wholesaler releases the platform operator from all third-party claims due to infringements of intellectual property rights.

6. Liability and Indemnification

6.1 The platform operator exclusively provides the technical infrastructure for brokering transactions between wholesalers and retailers. The platform operator assumes no liability for the conclusion of contracts, the economic expediency of individual transactions or the success of offers.

6.2 The platform operator is not liable for offers, product quality, delivery capability, delivery times, tax treatment, customs obligations or other obligations of the wholesaler towards third parties.

6.3 The wholesaler is solely responsible for:

– Product quality
– Product safety
– Delivery times
– tax obligations
– customs matters
– Labeling requirements
– Marketability of the goods offered

6.4 The platform operator is only liable for damages that are due to intentional or grossly negligent behavior. In the case of slight negligence, the platform operator is only liable for breach of essential contractual obligations (cardinal obligations) and is limited to the typically foreseeable damage.

6.5 Liability of the platform operator for indirect damages, consequential damages or lost profits is - to the extent permitted by law - excluded.

6.6 The platform operator is not liable for damages or failures caused by technical disruptions beyond its control, in particular due to:

– Internet or telecommunications network failures
– Disruptions to hosting or cloud service providers
– Attacks on the IT infrastructure (e.g. hacker attacks, DDoS attacks, malware)
– unauthorized access by third parties
– Interference caused by external software or interfaces

6.7 The platform operator is also not liable for damages resulting from force majeure events. These include, in particular, natural disasters, war, terrorist attacks, government measures, strikes, pandemics, energy outages or comparable unforeseeable events.

6.8 If the platform operator provides free services or additional functions, there is no guarantee of availability or freedom from errors.

6.9 If claims are made against the platform operator by authorities, competitors, brand owners or other third parties due to actions, offers or breaches of duty by the wholesaler, the wholesaler will release the platform operator from all claims.

6.10 The exemption includes in particular:

– Claims for damages
– Injunctive relief
– Warning costs
– Court and legal fees
– official fees
– other legal defense costs

6.11 The wholesaler undertakes to provide the platform operator with appropriate support in defending against such claims and to provide all the information necessary for this.

6.12 To the extent permitted by law, the platform operator's total liability arising from or in connection with this contract is limited to the amount of the platform fees that the wholesaler paid to the platform operator in the last quarter before the occurrence of the event giving rise to liability.

6.13 The above limitations of liability do not apply to damages resulting from injury to life, body or health or in cases of mandatory statutory liability.

7. Sanctions and contractual penalties

7.1 If the wholesaler violates legal regulations, the provisions of this contract, the platform's compliance rules or other binding guidelines of the platform operator, the platform operator is entitled to take appropriate measures.

7.2 When selecting the measures, the platform operator is guided by the principle of proportionality. In principle, the mildest appropriate means should be chosen that is capable of ending the violation and preventing future violations.

7.3 Possible measures can in particular be:

– Notice or warning
– Request for immediate correction of an offer
– temporary removal of individual offers
– Restriction of individual platform functions
– temporary account suspension
– permanent account ban
– Termination of the contract for good cause
– Claiming a contractual penalty

7.4 Particularly serious violations may warrant action without prior warning. This applies in particular to:

– Offering or distributing illegal goods
– criminally relevant conduct
– Violations of customs or foreign trade law
– serious trademark or intellectual property rights violations
– Manipulation of the platform or technical infrastructure
– systematic bypassing of the platform

7.5 In the event of significant or repeated breaches of contract, the platform operator is entitled to impose an appropriate contractual penalty. As a guideline, a contractual penalty of up to 1% of the wholesaler's net sales achieved via the platform in the last completed quarter can be used for each violation identified. In the case of persistent or repeated violations, the contractual penalty can be set separately for each individual violation. The specific amount is determined by the platform operator at its reasonable discretion, taking into account the severity of the violation, the degree of culpability, the duration of the breach of duty and the economic impact on the platform. The wholesaler reserves the right to prove that no damage or significantly less damage has occurred.

7.6 The assertion of further claims for damages remains unaffected.

7.7 Measures under this section may also be applied in combination if this appears necessary to maintain the integrity of the platform.

8. Platform Availability

8.1 The platform operator makes the platform available within the scope of technical and economic possibilities. There is no claim to uninterrupted or error-free availability of the platform at any time.

8.2 The platform operator is entitled to carry out maintenance work, updates, technical adjustments or expansions of the platform to the extent that this is necessary to maintain the functionality, security or further development of the platform.

8.3 Planned maintenance work should - as far as possible - take place outside of the platform users' usual business hours. This particularly includes night times or weekends. However, there is no entitlement to this.

8.4 The platform operator is entitled to carry out short-term maintenance or security measures without prior notice if this is necessary to avert security risks, to stabilize the platform or to prevent misuse.

8.5 The platform operator is also entitled to change, expand, restrict or discontinue functions of the platform, provided this is reasonable taking into account the legitimate interests of the users.

8.6 The platform operator is not liable for failures or restrictions on the platform that are beyond its immediate control. These include in particular:

– Internet or telecommunications network failures
– Disruptions to hosting, cloud or infrastructure service providers
– Cyber attacks, DDoS attacks or other IT security incidents
– Errors or failures of external interfaces or software components
– Power outages or infrastructure disruptions

8.7 The platform operator assumes no guarantee that the platform is compatible at all times with all systems used by the wholesaler, in particular merchandise management systems or external interfaces.

8.8 The platform operator is entitled to continuously develop the platform. This may include, in particular, changes to user interfaces, technical interfaces, functions or business processes.

8.9 Temporary restrictions on platform availability do not entitle the wholesaler to reduce, withhold or reduce platform fees, unless mandatory legal regulations conflict with this.

9. Term and Termination

9.1 The contract runs for an indefinite period of time.

9.2 Termination occurs at the request of the wholesaler or by termination of the platform operator.

9.3 It is not possible for the wholesaler to delete the account independently.

9.4 The platform operator is entitled to delete the data only after outstanding invoices have been clarified.

9.5 The right to extraordinary termination for good cause remains unaffected.

10. Fees and Billing

10.1 The platform operator charges a sales-dependent platform fee for using the platform. The fee is calculated based on the transactions generated and documented via the platform.

10.2 The initial platform fee is 1% of the wholesaler's net sales generated via the platform.

10.3 The platform operator is entitled to gradually adjust the platform fee as the platform continues to develop and taking market conditions into account. An increase in the platform fee can occur in particular if additional functions, increased reach, data-based services or expanded sales structures are provided. The platform fee can be adjusted to up to 3% of the revenue generated via the platform within a period of five years.

10.4 Changes to the fee structure will be announced to the wholesaler with a reasonable period of notice, usually at least three months before they come into force.

10.5 The platform operator creates an automated monthly invoice for the sales generated via the platform.

10.6 The basis for billing is all transactions documented via the platform in the respective billing month. Both positive sales and subsequent corrections are taken into account, in particular refunds, cancellations, chargebacks or other adjustments.

10.7 Billing is carried out according to the principle of periodically allocated sales. Sales are assigned to the month in which they were triggered via the platform. Subsequent adjustments, such as refunds or corrections, will be reflected in the following billing period.

10.8 The automated billing is generally made available to the wholesaler electronically by the third working day of a month for the previous month at the latest.

10.9 Payment of the stated platform fees is due no later than the seventh working day of the respective month.

10.10 The platform operator is entitled to provide invoices exclusively in electronic form.

10.11 The platform operator is entitled to offer further optional paid additional services, in particular in the area of ​​expanded platform functions, data analysis, premium placements, advertising formats or additional sales support. The use of such services only takes place after a separate agreement.

10.12 The platform operator is entitled to publish or update a separate fee schedule, which may contain additional details about the fee structure. Such a fee schedule becomes part of this contract.

11. Customs and authority matters

11.1 The wholesaler is solely responsible for all customs, foreign trade and tax obligations in connection with the goods offered or sold via the platform.

11.2 If customs authorities, tax authorities or other government bodies take action in connection with offers or transactions from a wholesaler via the platform, wholesalers and platform operators undertake to communicate openly and cooperatively.

11.3 The wholesaler undertakes to inform the platform operator immediately if there are official inquiries, checks, investigations or measures that are related to goods offered via the platform.

11.4 In such cases, a cooperative and amicable solution should first be sought between the wholesaler and the platform operator. Both parties undertake to exchange information and – where appropriate – to develop a coordinated strategy for dealing with authorities.

11.5 The platform operator is entitled to obtain legal advice to protect its legal interests. Information will generally only be passed on to authorities after legal review and to the extent that this appears legally necessary or expedient.

11.6 The platform operator will inform the wholesaler - to the extent legally permissible - about the type and extent of the information passed on to authorities and explain the reasons for this transparently.

11.7 If the platform operator is subject to claims by authorities due to actions or breaches of duty by the wholesaler or incurs costs as a result, the wholesaler undertakes to fully indemnify and cover the resulting expenses, in particular for legal advice, defense and official proceedings.

12. Confidentiality

12.1 Both parties undertake to treat all non-public information that they become aware of as part of the collaboration as confidential.

12.2 Confidential information includes in particular:

– Pricing models
– Offer structures and special conditions
– Sales strategies
– Customer and dealer data
– Transaction data
– technical information about the platform
– internal business processes
– economic indicators

12.3 Confidential Information may only be used for the purpose of carrying out this Agreement.

12.4 Passing on confidential information to third parties is only permitted if this is necessary to fulfill the contract or if there is a legal obligation to do so.

12.5 Both parties undertake to take appropriate organizational and technical measures to protect confidential information from unauthorized access.

12.6 The obligation of confidentiality continues even after the termination of this contract.

12.7 The obligation to maintain confidentiality continues for a period of three years after termination of the contract.

13. Applicable Law and Place of Jurisdiction

13.1 German law applies to the exclusion of international private law and the UN Convention on Contracts for the International Sale of Goods.

13.2 Place of jurisdiction is Hamburg, Germany, to the extent permitted by law.

14. Offsetting and retention rights

14.1 The wholesaler is only entitled to offset if his counterclaims have been legally established or are undisputed.

14.2 The platform operator is entitled to offset its own claims against outstanding claims of the wholesaler, to the extent this is legally permissible.

14.3 The wholesaler is only authorized to exercise a right of retention to the extent that his counterclaim is based on the same contractual relationship.

15. Audit, Control and Marketplace Protection Rights

15.1 The platform operator is entitled to request suitable evidence, documents or other information from the wholesaler if there is reasonable suspicion of serious contractual violations, in particular platform circumvention, compliance violations, misuse of the platform or violations of legal regulations.

15.2 In such a case, the wholesaler undertakes to provide the information required for clarification within a reasonable period of time, to the extent that this is reasonable.

15.3 The platform operator is entitled to take measures to ensure the integrity of the marketplace system. This includes, in particular, examinations of offers, transactions, price structures, offer behavior or unusual usage patterns.

15.4 The aim of these measures is, in particular, to protect the marketplace ecosystem from:

– systematic bypassing of the platform
– improper use of special offers
– manipulative supply structures
– behavior that is problematic under antitrust law
– technical manipulation of the platform
– other actions that are likely to impair the functionality or reputation of the platform

15.5 The platform operator is entitled to take preliminary measures if there is reasonable suspicion of such violations, in particular:

– temporary deactivation of individual offers
– Restriction of individual platform functions
– temporary account suspension
– Request additional verification documents

15.6 A further examination is carried out with appropriate protection of the wholesaler's legitimate business and trade secrets.

15.7 These control rights serve exclusively to protect the functionality, legal security and integrity of the marketplace operation.

16. Assignment and Transfer of Contract

16.1 The wholesaler is not entitled to assign any rights or obligations under this contract without the consent of the platform operator.

16.2 The platform operator is entitled to transfer this contract to an affiliated company as part of a restructuring, a company sale or a transfer of platform parts.

17. Data analysis, ranking and algorithm mechanisms

17.1 The wholesaler acknowledges that the platform operator is entitled to evaluate aggregated transaction, usage and market data in order to ensure the operation, security, economic efficiency and further development of the platform.

17.2 The evaluation can be carried out in particular for:

– Analysis of demand and supply structures
– Optimization of offer presentations
– Preparation of market analyses
– Forecasting sales developments
– Improve product recommendations
– Further development of data-based platform functions

17.3 The platform operator is entitled to use ranking, recommendation or visibility mechanisms within the platform based on this data.

17.4 The placement of offers within the platform can be influenced in particular by the following factors:

– Demand and sales development
– Pricing and offer attractiveness
– Reliability and delivery performance of the wholesaler
– Offer quality and data completeness
– User interactions within the platform
– Platform-internal quality or reputation indicators

17.5 The platform operator is entitled to use algorithmic systems to sort, display or recommend offers. There is no entitlement to a specific placement, visibility or prioritization of offers.

17.6 The platform operator may use internal reputation or rating systems to assess the quality of offers, the reliability of merchants or the stability of transactions.

17.7 Such systems may in particular take into account:

– Contract fulfillment rates
– Delivery reliability
– Transaction stability
– Complaint or cancellation rates
– Compliance with platform rules

17.8 The platform operator is entitled to adapt the functionality of such analysis, ranking or reputation mechanisms as part of the further development of the platform, provided that this does not result in unreasonable disadvantage for individual wholesalers.

17.9 Personal data will only be processed within the framework of the applicable data protection regulations.

17.10 The wholesaler acknowledges that the platform operator is entitled to create aggregated and anonymized data sets from the transaction, usage and market data generated via the platform.

17.11 The platform operator is entitled to use such aggregated or anonymized data for its own commercial purposes, in particular to prepare market analyses, industry reports, statistical evaluations, data-based services and to provide analysis or information services to third parties.

17.12 Individual transaction data or confidential company information from the wholesaler will not be passed on unless there is a legal obligation to do so or the wholesaler has expressly consented.

17.13 The platform operator is entitled to develop and commercially exploit new functions, data-based services, analysis products or other further developments of the platform based on the data, insights and usage patterns obtained via the platform, provided that no confidential individual information from the wholesaler is disclosed.

17.14 All data sets, models, forecasts, rankings, statistical evaluations, market analyzes or comparable data-based results (“Derived Data”) derived from the analysis, aggregation or other processing of the platform data are the sole property of the platform operator. The wholesaler does not acquire any rights to this. This applies in particular to algorithmic models, analysis methods, ranking mechanisms, databases and data-based products or services developed from them.

18. API and Interface Usage

18.1 The use of technical interfaces is at the wholesaler’s own risk.

18.2 The wholesaler undertakes not to carry out any security-threatening, manipulative or technically abusive interventions in the platform.

18.3 In particular, automated access, manipulation of interfaces or circumvention of technical protection mechanisms are not permitted unless they have been expressly approved by the platform operator.

19. Competition, Anti-Circumvention and Network Effects Protection

19.1 The wholesaler undertakes not to systematically continue or conclude business relationships initiated via the platform outside of the platform if this is intended to avoid platform fees or undermine the economic operation of the marketplace.

19.2 This applies in particular to situations in which dealers or retailers permanently switch to external communication or sales channels to process transactions outside of the platform after initial contact via the platform.

19.3 The wholesaler further undertakes not to take any technical, organizational or contractual measures that aim to specifically circumvent the functionality of the marketplace system or impair its economic basis.

19.4 In order to protect the network effects created by the Marketplace, the wholesaler undertakes in particular not to systematically use the market information, dealer contacts or sales structures obtained via the platform to set up competing digital trading platforms.

19.5 In particular, the following is not permitted:

– the systematic extraction or collection of dealer or offer data
– the use of platform data to develop competing marketplace structures
– the targeted poaching of platform participants to set up a competing system

19.6 The wholesaler's usual participation in other trading platforms or sales channels remains permissible, provided that there is no targeted use of the structural market information obtained via this platform.

19.7 If these provisions are culpably violated, the platform operator may take measures in accordance with Section 7 (Sanctions and Contractual Penalties).

20. Limitation period

20.1 Contractual claims arising from this contract expire - to the extent permitted by law - within twelve months of becoming aware of the facts giving rise to the claim.

21. Written form/text form

21.1 Changes and additions to this contract must at least be in text form.

22. Severability clause

Should a provision of this contract be or become wholly or partially ineffective, the effectiveness of the remaining provisions remains unaffected.
